    "methodology": "One-year survival is measured as the proportion of adults diagnosed with cancer who survive at least one year after diagnosis, age-standardised. Late-stage diagnosis refers to cancers diagnosed at stage III or IV. Screening uptake is measured as the proportion of eligible individuals screened within the target period.",
    "knownIssues": [
      "COVID-19 caused major diagnostic disruption in 2020 — fewer cancers were diagnosed, and those that were tended to be more advanced, temporarily depressing survival figures",
      "Staging completeness has improved over time, meaning apparent increases in late-stage diagnosis may partly reflect better recording",
      "International comparisons use ICBP data which may differ slightly from ONS national figures due to methodology differences"
